{"key":"post-11185682","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11185682</id>\n<content>Soil mixes were popular 20 to 30 years ago in casing layers.&amp;nbsp; However, you will have a higher rate of contamination then a plain peat/verm casing that has been buffered with lime, and had gypsum added.&amp;nbsp; It all depends on the species you're wanting to grow.&amp;nbsp; Many don't require or benefit from a casing layer.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You 'can' pasteurize in the oven, but it will take much longer.&amp;nbsp; Put a meat thermometer into the substrate and keep it between 140F and 160F (60C to 70C) for one hour at the center.&amp;nbsp; Water is a much better heat transfer media than air, so it's generally faster to use hot water pasteurization.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11185737</next>\n<prev>11185649</prev>\n<first>11179726</first>\n<last>11185737</last>\n<when>1254755119</when>\n<utime>10/05/09 06:05 PM</utime>\n</post>"}